We can make sense of sounds with our understanding of syntax and grammar.
Syntactic Ambiguity ‚ùî Ordering and structure between words can be grouped into &lsquo;parse tree&rsquo; structures given grammatical &lsquo;rules&rsquo;.
E.g. &ldquo;I shot an elephant in my pajamas&rdquo;
Is the elephant wearing your pajamas?
Semantic Resolution ‚§µÔ∏è We can resolve ambiguities because of our knowledge of semantics (meaning), but that won&rsquo;t always be the case.
Semantic Ambiguity ‚ùî How is meaning created by use of words and phrases?
&ldquo;Every man loves a woman&rdquo;
\(\forall x \: man(x) \exists y: (woman(y) \wedge loves (x,y))\) \(\exists y: woman(y) \wedge \forall x :\ (man(x) \rightarrow loves (x,y))\) &ldquo;I made her duck&rdquo;
I cooked waterfowl meat for her to eat. I cooked waterfowl that belonged to her. I carved the wooden duck that she owns. I caused her to quickly lower her head. &ldquo;Give me the pot&rdquo;
It&rsquo;s time to bake. It&rsquo;s time to get baked. Pragmatics Resolution ‚§µÔ∏è ‚ùì No one woman is so popular right? Yeah there isn&rsquo;t.
